ga.gen: General: Upturned, dainty bill. Droops neck in flight. Light color, relatively slender.

similar: Arctic loon- other loons- grebes and cormorants
ga.gen: General: Lack of white flank distinguishes it from Arctic loon.
tips: Arctic loons MAY occur extremely rarely in the area as a migrant. Likely never occurs here and all similar animals are assumed to be Pacific. Arctic loons have white flank patches

similar: Yellow-billed loon- other loons- grebes and cormorants
ga.gen: General: Thick bird. Big lumpy head. Dagger-like bill. Does not droop head. Bill changes color according to plumage. Sits low in water.

similar: Common loon- other loons- grebes and cormorants
ga.gen: General: Larger than Common loon. Yellow bill in all stages. Feathers are brown/tan in alls stages
General: Little chicken grebe with stubby bill. Smallest grebe in the area.
General:
tips: Eared grebes MAY ocurs as a vagrant in the area but it is assumed that they don't

ga.gen: General:
tips: Adult nonbreeding and 1st winter will be treated as identical

similar: Red-throated loon, other loons and cormorants in flight
ga.gen: General: Tall with slender neck and thin sharp bill.
tips: Clarks grebe MAY occur as a vagrant in the area but is not likely to. It is assumed they don't.

ga.gen: General: Unmistakable in the area; almost black; shallow wing beats, fast flight, classic tube-nose bill.
General: Unmistakable in the area; almost black; shallow wing beats, fast flight, classic tube-nose bill.
General: WHITE RUMP PATCH! Otherwise dark, almost black. Storm petrels are small birds with slender, long wings. Have diagnostic bouyant, fast wing beats. Enormous forehead, small hooked bill.

General: NO WHITE RUMP PATCH. Otherwise gray with dark "M" on wings. Storm petrels are small birds with slender, long wings. Have diagnostic bouyant, fast wing beats. Enormous forehead, small hooked bill.

similar: Other cormorants, loons and grebes in flight
ga.gen: General: Orange/yellow face. Largest cormorant, with thick crooked neck. Neck remains crooked in flight.

similar: DC is more like brandt's.Other cormorants, loons and grebes in flight
ga.gen: General: Smallest, most slender local cormorant. Snake-like neck and very thin bill. Red face, with oily-purple plumage as an adult.

similar: Brandts is more like DC. Other cormorants, loons and grebes in flight
ga.gen: General: Middle cormorant in the area. Blue face. Thick neck but not crooked. Intermediate in all respects.
General: Enormous white swan.
tips: Tundra swam may occur in area but it is pooled with Trumpeter

ga.gen: General: Classic grey and black goose with white face.
General: More tan/yellow than the other geese, with orange and white face markings that stand out at a distance. Larger than Canadian.

General:

ga.gen: General: Pointed tail feathers.
tips: Male breeding pintails are known. All other pintails are pooled: nonbreeding males and females, breeding females and juveniles

ga.gen: General: Enormous but slender bill.
tips: Juvenile of both sexes and adult female are indistinguishible. Male can be distinguished at both adult nonbreeding and adult breeding

General: Enormous sea duck. Rarest scoter in area during summer. No white markings on male's face or either sex's wings.
General: Enormous sea duck, most common locally by far. Clown face. No white on wings.
General: Enormous sea duck. Second most common scoter. White on wings is diagnostic among scoters.

General: The only expected pharalope in the area. Face mask curves down cheek (it curves up in Red phalaope). White "M" chevron in flight. Top heavy and long of neck while sitting, but tucks neck in flight to appear very different. Classic "flock tacking" tactic while crossing bodies of water.
General: Largest and darkest jaeger.
tips: least frequent inland jaeger in most of the west

ga.gen: General: The intermediate jaeger.
General: Smallest local jaeger. Little to no collar; lightest plumage.
tips: usually solitary; rarely steals food; smallest and most elegant

ga.gen: General: Smallest area gull. Bill always black.

General : Longer bill, longer legs, and much more black on wing tips than Arctic tern.
General: Shorter bill, shorter legs, and much less black on wng tips than Common tern.
General: Large alcidenormous honker and funny hair-do.
General: Large with long dagger-like bill, almost confused with loons.
General: Orange feet! White wing patches (sitting and in flight), round head and short bill (like Cassin's but much bigger overall).

General: Large, hulky alcid. Just slightly smaller than Common murre. Humped, strong back in flight. Short wing aspect-ratio compared to murrelets, but much larger overall. Strong but blunt bill is unique among local alcids.

General: Small alcid, between rhino and marbled in size. Very round head, short triangular beak and permanent white eyepatch (but difficult to see at a distance). Tied with marbled murrelet for worst take offs.

General: Thin, short bill and FLAT FOREHEAD. Smallest alcid in area, but long wings in flight make it look bigger. Plumage changes dramatically throughout summer. Tied with Cassin's auklet for worst take offs and landings.
tips: Key in productivity estimates is AHY/HY distinction, which requires close approach.

ga.gen: General: Small alcid, very like marbled murrelet but more elegant plumage. White eyebrow. NEVER HAS A WHITE SHOULDER STRAP.
General: Enormous head, lands in trees, usually seen only entering and leaving coves but noteworthy when seen crossing a sound.
General: Inordinate size, broad eagle wings with long soaring primaries, wimpy call. The most common raptor in the area. Scrappy juveniles can look like more crytpic hawk species.
General: Huge eyes, small bill, round head too large for body.
